		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/06/28/us/28fd-abortionreax-LN/28fd-abortionreax-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/06/28/us/28fd-abortionreax-LN/28fd-abortionreax-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/06/28/us/28fd-abortionreax-LN/28fd-abortionreax-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000004606636" width="592" height="395" alt="Demonstrators gathered in front of the United States Supreme Court in Washington in June. The court struck down parts of a restrictive abortion law in Texas. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2016/06/28/us/politics/scotus-abortion-ruling-reaction.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Demonstrators gathered in front of the United States Supreme Court in Washington in June. The court struck down parts of a restrictive abortion law in Texas. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2016/06/28/us/politics/scotus-abortion-ruling-reaction.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Zach Gibson/The New York Times</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/08/24/election-2016-unit-part-2-what-are-the-issues/" data-title="Election 2016 Unit, Part 2: What Are the Issues?" data-description="For this second mini-unit, students continue working as investigative reporters learning about the issues at stake in this election. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">All week long we are publishing sections of our <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/tag/election-unit-2016/">Election Unit</a>, each day&#8217;s post a new &#8220;mini-unit&#8221; based on an essential question. All five posts work together to take students through a series of hands-on research and presentation projects that will help them understand the candidates and the issues in this year&#8217;s presidential race.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Monday we gave an <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/08/22/our-election-2016-unit-an-overview/">overview of the entire unit</a>, including goals, essential questions and projects.  Tuesday we explained how the unit begins with students becoming <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/08/23/election-2016-unit-part-1-who-are-the-candidates/">reporters investigating the candidates</a>. Below, the campaign issues.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-170377"></span></p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Mini-Unit 2: The Issues</strong><br />
<strong>Essential Question 2: What Are the Issues?</strong><br />
<strong>Projects: Multi-Issue Voter Guide and Structured Debate</strong></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Overview:</strong> For this second mini-unit, students continue working as investigative reporters, but instead of researching the candidates&#8217; biographies, they are now learning about the issues at stake in this election. Their task is to create a tool to help voters understand where the candidates stand on the most important issues. Then they hold a debate. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Survey or Interview:</strong> To begin Mini-Unit 2, students take a survey of what issues matter most to them. The survey can be a simple open-ended question &#8212; âWhat three issues in this election matter most to you?â &#8212; or it can include a list of preselected issues that students rank. Students can interview a partner or take the survey individually. Below are some possible issues:</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Jobs and the Economy<br />
Education and College<br />
Energy and the Environment<br />
Immigration<br />
Tax Policy<br />
Health Care<br />
Foreign Policy and Defense<br />
Social Issues<br />
Terrorism<br />
Guns and Violence</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Issue Research:</strong> While students are likely to be familiar with certain candidate stances, such as Donald Trump&#8217;s campaign pledge to build a wall along the entire United States-Mexico border, they are probably unsure or confused about where the candidates stand on other issues &#8212; perhaps the very issues that students care about most. For example, what do the candidates have to say about college affordability or income inequality?  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So, again, working in teams, pairs or individually, students should find out what the candidates think. You may choose to assign specific issues to students or to let them choose the issues they want to research. You can use the survey results from the previous activity to narrow the issues the class will cover. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We imagine that the research process begins with students getting a broad overview of the candidates and their positions. Then, once the class has a good understanding of where the candidates stand on key issues, students can shift their research so they become &#8220;experts&#8221; on one particular topic and what is at stake.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We prepared two graphic organizers to help guide student research. (Click on the images to download a PDF version.) </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs/learning/pdf/2016/IssuesChartLN2.pdf"><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/08/18/learning/CandidatesIssuesLN2a/CandidatesIssuesLN2a-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/08/18/learning/CandidatesIssuesLN2a/CandidatesIssuesLN2a-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/08/18/learning/CandidatesIssuesLN2a/CandidatesIssuesLN2a-blog480.jpg" id="100000004599623" width="480" height="126" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="126"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div></a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After students work on the broad picture, they can become experts on a single issue by using the second organizer (another PDF).</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs/learning/pdf/2016/OneIssueChart2016LN.pdf"><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/08/18/learning/CandidateSingleIssueLN/CandidateSingleIssueLN-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/08/18/learning/CandidateSingleIssueLN/CandidateSingleIssueLN-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2016/08/18/learning/CandidateSingleIssueLN/CandidateSingleIssueLN-blog480.jpg" id="100000004599648" width="480" height="127" alt=""   /><meta itemprop="height" content="127"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text"></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> </span></figcaption></figure></div></a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Resources for Issue Research:</strong> We&#8217;ve gathered resources that can be useful for students doing research on where the candidates stand on different election issues. We will update this post as new resources become available.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The nonprofit, nonpartisan organization <a href="//2016election.procon.org/view.source-summary-chart.php">ProCon.org</a> offers a side-by-side comparison of where all the 2016 presidential candidates stand on dozens of issues. When students click on an issue, they will see relevant quotes made by the various candidates.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="https://www.isidewith.com/candidate-guide/donald-trump-vs-hillary-clinton">ISideWith</a>, <a href="https://www.washingtonpost.com/graphics/politics/political-issues/">The Washington Post</a> and <a href="//digg.com/2016/trump-hillary-clinton-comparison">Digg</a> also offer comparisons of Mr. Trump and Hillary Clinton on various issues.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A number of sites provide side-by-side comparisons on specific issues, such as <a href="//www.edweek.org/ew/section/multimedia/president-candidates-trump-clinton-education.html">education</a>, the <a href="//graphics.wsj.com/elections/2016/donald-trump-hillary-clinton-on-the-economy/">economy</a>, <a href="//www.cfr.org/campaign2016/">foreign policy</a> and <a href="//www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2016/jul/15/compare-candidates-clinton-vs-trump-immigration/">immigration</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In addition, the <a href="https://www.hillaryclinton.com/issues/">Clinton</a> and <a href="https://www.donaldjtrump.com/positions">Trump</a> websites provide the official candidate positions on many issues.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If students want to do additional research in The Times on how the issues are playing out in the campaign, they can use the <a href="//query.nytimes.com/search/sitesearch/">advanced search feature</a>. Or they can  go directly to the index pages for the most up-to-date <a href="//www.nytimes.com/pages/politics/index.html">politics articles</a> and <a href="//www.nytimes.com/video/landing/politics/1194811622221/index.html">videos</a>.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Project 1 | Multi-Issue Voter Guide:</strong> Working in teams, students create a tool to inform voters about where the candidates stand on the most important issues. Teachers or teams can decide what form this tool should take. It could be a poster, chart or <a href="//www.dailyinfographic.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/11/yahoo-ask-america-large.jpg">infographic</a>, for example. Or, it could be an &#8220;explainer&#8221; article, <a href="//www.newsy.com/videos/election-issues-of-2016-education/">video</a> or <a href="//uvilklixbzaa74f345wrd9kd.wpengine.netdna-cdn.com/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/MassVoterTable_Flyer2013_0414v3.pdf">voter guide</a> (PDF). </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Presentation:</strong> All these campaign materials are perfect to use in a mock election, and a real audience for student work is a powerful motivator.  If you are not planning to hold a mock election, then these materials could be presented in different formats.  For example, students could walk around the classroom looking at one another&#8217;s work displayed in a &#8220;gallery&#8221; on walls and desks.  Students could also present their work in front the class.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Either way, encourage students to look closely at the projects and think about which candidate best matches with their own positions. They can use this information during the final mini-unit when they write their own endorsement of a particular candidate. Students can also give and receive peer feedback on each other&#8217;s projects, perhaps using the handout below. (Click on the image to download a PDF version.) </p>
<div class="w480"><a href="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs/learning/pdf/2016/PresentationPeerFeedbackLN2.pdf"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/08/21/learning/IssuePeerFeedbackLN/IssuePeerFeedbackLN-blog480.jpg" id="100000001733658" width="480" height="155" alt="" /><span class="credit"></span><span class="caption"></span></a></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Project 2 | Structured Debate:</strong> In addition to having students create campaign materials, or as an alternative to that project, students could hold a debate on the issues. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Debates can take place in many formats, and we write about several in our post, <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/05/17/great-debate-developing-argumentation-skills/">&#8220;Great Debate: Developing Argumentation Skills.&#8221;</a>  If students become &#8220;experts&#8221; on a single issue during their research, then a Structured Academic Controversy would give all students the opportunity to participate in a mini-debate about health care policy or immigration reform, or whatever issue they researched.  Our lesson <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/02/05/on-dont-ask-dont-tell-debating-a-proposed-repeal/">&#8220;On âDonât Ask, Donât Tellâ: Debating a Proposed Repeal&#8221;</a> provides detailed instructions for how to organize this kind of debate.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another debate format that can keep the whole class engaged is a Roundtable Discussion, similar to the format in the TV program <a href="//video.nytimes.com/video/2009/08/16/health/policy/1247464047301/health-care-debate-on-meet-the-press.html">&#8220;Meet the Press.&#8221;</a> In this type of debate, a small group of students sits in the center or front of the classroom as a panel of experts while the rest of the class listens and takes notes.  Students in the &#8220;audience&#8221; could be waiting for their turn to participate in the discussion as new issues come up, or they could be formulating questions to ask the roundtable members.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">You may want to encourage students to give one another feedback on their debate performance using the <a href="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs/learning/pdf/2010/20100517evaluatedebate.pdf">Evaluate a Debate</a> (PDF) handout or a similar feedback form.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Reflections:</strong> And at the end of one or both projects, students can answer the following questions:</p>
<ul>
<li>What did you learn about the issues in this election that surprised you or that you didnât know before?</li>
<li>Do you think your research findings would help an undecided voter choose a candidate? Why?</li>
<li>Which candidate do agree with most on the issues you care about? Why? </li>
</ul>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Thursday we will post our Election Unit&#8217;s <a href="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/08/25/election-2016-unit-part-3-the-campaign-strategy/">third mini-unit</a>, which focuses on campaign strategies and how the candidates will try to win the election. </p>
	</div>
